<font color="#FF0000">A HORSE W/NO NAME&amp; GEORGE TANK</font><br>
<tt>Wed Aug 20  1:29:36 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Edward,<br>
     You are absolutely right, I never learned to ride worth a damn.  The last time I tried was in college, and my rear kept moving in opposite directions to the saddle on the horse.  This did not suit either of us.  I also swim like a rock.<br><br>
     When I got back from Vietnam bought a '64 Lincoln with 46,000 miles that was on sale as a loss leader for $1345.  It was a good car to have fighting 40 mph cross winds on the Great Plains between Milwaukee and Fort Carson.  After my marriage, Gloria and I christened it &quot;George Tank&quot;.  It went some places no heavy sedan should be forced to traverse like Mosquito Pass, 13,188' elevation and paved with boulders between South Park and Leadville. After 60,000 miles in 3 years, the transmission died, and it was left behind when we moved to Pa.<br><br>
Cook,<br>
     You would enjoy meeting Gunny Frank Thompson from here in Philly.  He's equal opportunity politically incorrect - anyone's fair game.<br><br>
     Dale Dye was given an award at the VVA National Convention, and gave a blunt, very funny and rather profane acceptance speech.  He used the term &quot;Communist&quot; almost as much as you do.  Afterwards, just as the dance portion of the evening was starting, he marched all the Marines attending in formation to the area in front of the stage, and did a scene from &quot;A Few Good Men&quot;.  There he was, still lean as a whip, blasting away, and the guys are trying to play the part, attempting to suck in the uncompressable. Lines like &quot;What are you scumbags doing fucking up MY Marine Corps!?&quot; or worse blistered the air.  Still remember him walking up to one guy that now had long hair, a pony tail and flowing beard saying, &quot;YOU, get a hair cut!...GET FOUR HAIRCUTS!&quot;
<p><code>-- gerald_ney@icpphil.navy.mil  (Gerald Ney, &quot;professor&quot;, 7/68-7/69) </code><p>


